%text First, know what $f(x)$ is % \[ f(x) = \begin{cases}
-x + (1-x) = 1-2x\text{ for } x < 0 \\ x + (1-x) = 1\text{ for } 0\leq x < 1 \\ x + (x-1) = 2x - 1 \text{ for } x \geq 1 \end{cases} \] %text And hence at $x=0$ % \begin{align}
\lim_{x\to 0^-} f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 0^-} \left(1-2x \right) = 1 \\ \lim_{x\to 0^+} f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 0^+} \left(1 \right) = 1 \\ \end{align} %text $\lim_{x\to 0} f(x) = f(0) = 1$. Therefore, $f(x)$ is continuous at $x=0$ Similarly, at $x=1$ % \begin{align}
\lim_{x\to 1^-} f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 1^-} \left(1\right) = 1 \\ \lim_{x\to 1^+} f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 1^+} \left(2x-1 \right) = 1 \\ \end{align} %text Again $\lim_{x\to 1}f(x) = f(1)$. Hence, $f(x)$ is continuous at $x=1$ also%
